$ Preprocessor: predefined macros
@ predefined macros

→ development/languages/C-C-plus-plus/preprocessor/macros/predefined/__COUNTER__[`__COUNTER__`]

→ development/languages/C-C-plus-plus/preprocessor/macros/predefined/__FUNCTION__FILE__LINE__[`__FUNCTION__`, `__FILE__` and `__LINE__`].

`→ development/languages/C-C-plus-plus/preprocessor/macros/predefined/__cplusplus`


In order to describe the → development/languages/C-C-plus-plus/C/language/datatypes/wchar_t[`wchar_t`] datatype, there is → development/languages/C-C-plus-plus/C/language/datatypes/wchar_t#wchar_t-macros[`WCHAR_MAX`] (and further macros such as
  `__WCHAR_MAX__` and `__WCHAR_TYPE__` in → development/languages/C-C-plus-plus/GCC/index[gcc]).

{ Print predefined macros on the command line

  With the GNU compiler's command line option → development/languages/C-C-plus-plus/GCC/options/dM[`-dM`], it's possible to quickly show the values of predefined macros..
  -
  For example, in → Windows/PowerShell like so:
code {
→ Windows/PowerShell/command-inventory/noun/output/write '' | g++ -dM → development/languages/C-C-plus-plus/GCC/options/E → development/languages/C-C-plus-plus/GCC/options/x[-x] c++  -
code }

  Compare wtih → development/languages/C-C-plus-plus/preprocessor/macros/predefined/environment

}

sa:
  → development/languages/C-C-plus-plus/GCC/options/dM[`gcc -dM`]
